Durban - “It’s better to have the skills and not need them than to not know how to do it and need the skills.” This was the sentiments expressed by Barry Mohan, training manager at Crisis Medical. Mohan was speaking to the Daily News during National Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation (CPR) Week, which takes place from November 4 - 10 annually. Cardiopulmonary resuscitation or CPR is an emergency procedure. It is performed in an effort to manually preserve intact brain function until further measures are taken to restore spontaneous blood circulation and breathing in a person who is in cardiac arrest.  To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video “It is very important for all people to have basic CPR skills,” Mohan said.  To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video He said courses are offered for children, from the age of 12 and adults. What you should keep in your First Aid kit:   Medicines should be checked regularly to make sure they're within their use-by dates. Daily News